You got to have one-on-ones to have those, and then there's also some other topics that

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:51.279
maybe aren't so obvious that are important, so I'd like to talk just a little bit more

00:03:51.279 --> 00:03:52.279
about that.

00:03:52.279 --> 00:03:56.800
So I'm not a neurologist, know very little about the brain, but I did take my psych classes,

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:02.639
and so to set this up, maybe you've been in a meeting where someone was talking about

00:04:02.639 --> 00:04:07.399
something and someone else kind of overreacted, maybe didn't just overreact a little but seemed

00:04:07.399 --> 00:04:12.600
to kind of freak out over something relatively innocuous, well, we have some brain chemistry

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:13.839
going on there.

00:04:13.839 --> 00:04:19.399
The prefrontal cortex is the part of your brain that's responsible for logic and rationality

00:04:19.399 --> 00:04:21.640
and deep work and all this great stuff.

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:27.799
We also have amygdalas that were really important to human surviving and all these things along

00:04:27.799 --> 00:04:28.799
those years.

00:04:28.799 --> 00:04:30.000
Well, what does the amygdala do?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:31.000
It's scanning the environment.

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:35.959
It's scanning the environment, looking for danger, and if danger comes up, it tells your

00:04:35.959 --> 00:04:40.200
prefrontal cortex, hey, quiet down, we don't have any time for your crap, we need to fight

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:41.200
or flight.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:46.880
Well, the fact of the matter is group meetings are complex environments, and so you have

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:51.359
this risk of actually having that amygdala trigger over something maybe that didn't seem

00:04:51.359 --> 00:04:56.000
like it deserved it, but it triggers it, shuts down rationality, you get that overreaction,

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.959
and it can really cause a lot of damage that you can stay with a team for a long time.

00:05:01.399 --> 00:05:05.640
So we have these really important topics, not just about career growth, but about other

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:08.160
things that are best covered in a one-on-one.

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:12.040
So hopefully I've made the case that one-on-ones are pretty important.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:16.399
Again, we got better one-on-ones, we're building trust between team members, that results in

00:05:16.399 --> 00:05:17.720
stronger teams over time.

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:20.440
What I'd like to do is run through three different flavors.

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:21.679
There's some overlap here.

00:05:21.679 --> 00:05:23.480
You may have a different role in different ones.

00:05:23.480 --> 00:05:26.279
It's okay, there's a little bit of a lesson, hopefully, from any of them.

00:05:26.279 --> 00:05:29.839
We're going to talk about a goal for each one, and then we're going to talk about a

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:30.920
specific tactic.

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:35.000
Because in my experience, if you have a habit, if you can build it in, you can get better

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:36.640
at something and improve.

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:41.040
And if you don't have a simple thing to do to repeat, it's hard to kind of keep it front

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:43.279
of mind and keep getting better at it.

00:05:43.279 --> 00:05:49.880
So first type, most common type, probably the most important one, probably applies to

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:51.679
pretty much everyone here.

00:05:51.679 --> 00:05:53.799
We have a team lead and a team member.

00:05:53.799 --> 00:05:55.119
We're trying to build trust.

00:05:55.119 --> 00:05:57.839
We know that that's one of the goals I've already made the case for, that that's just

00:05:57.839 --> 00:06:00.519
so important to a team operating.

00:06:00.519 --> 00:06:02.920
And then we have the idea of establishing goals.

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:06.600
And by establishing goals, I mean, what's the group goals?

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:09.239
You want to make sure we're on the same page and understanding of that.

00:06:09.239 --> 00:06:11.160
We also have individual goals.

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:13.920
And really what we want is alignment between them.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:18.160
So a really good career conversation, again, one of those foundational one-on-one ideas,

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:22.320
is getting aligned of, hey, I'm really interested in learning this thing, and hey, the team

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:23.320
has a gap in that.

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:24.559
Let's put them together.

00:06:24.559 --> 00:06:26.040
That's a great career conversation.

00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:31.040
That's going to set both the team and the individual up to be successful within it.

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:32.040
Giving feedback.

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:34.760
Obviously, one-on-ones are a really important place to do that.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:36.040
And I mean both ways.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:39.480
Giving feedback isn't just team lead to team manager.

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:44.760
It is both team lead to the team member and back, vice versa.

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:50.279
So one of the things that I learned over time, or I got taught, let's say, about management

00:06:50.279 --> 00:06:54.440
and doing one-on-ones is, well, if you have to give someone feedback, you feed them a

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:56.480
crap sandwich.

00:06:56.480 --> 00:06:58.119
So we have a piece of bread.

00:06:58.119 --> 00:06:59.359
I guess that's the good part.

00:06:59.359 --> 00:07:03.320
And then we have the harsh criticism maybe in the middle.

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:04.399
So I guess that's the crap.

00:07:04.399 --> 00:07:08.640
And then another piece of bread on the other end to make a sandwich of it.

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:10.000
My experience, that's fine.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:11.959
You definitely want a mix of good and bad things.

00:07:11.959 --> 00:07:14.799
You want to predominate with good as much as you can.

00:07:14.799 --> 00:07:19.640
Focus on positives where you can, not avoiding the important feedback when it comes up.

00:07:19.679 --> 00:07:25.119
But in my experience, it's much better to start with a, here's a specific observation.

00:07:25.119 --> 00:07:29.200
This is something that happened in as factual terms as I can.

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:30.839
And then ask questions about it.

00:07:30.839 --> 00:07:33.359
Don't assume you know that everything's going on.

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:34.679
That is a form of feedback.

00:07:34.679 --> 00:07:36.480
Hey, here's this behavior.

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:37.940
Maybe it had some consequences.

00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:39.200
Maybe it wasn't ideal.

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:40.320
But let's talk about it.

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:41.600
I want to understand it better.

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:44.279
I want to see where you're coming from and make sure I get it.

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:46.320
That's the two version of feedback.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:50.079
And then you can turn up the volume as you get comfortable, as you understand the person

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:51.079
and how they react.

00:07:51.079 --> 00:07:55.359
Because some people, you can say all the great things in the world and have one little negative

00:07:55.359 --> 00:07:56.359
one.

00:07:56.359 --> 00:07:57.359
They're going to obsess about the negative one.

00:07:57.359 --> 00:07:59.920
And your next five one-on-ones will be affected by that.

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:02.959
Other people, they'll only hear the positives.

00:08:02.959 --> 00:08:07.040
You said something you felt was pretty direct and somehow flies right over their head.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:08.040
They miss it.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:12.480
So you got to be attentive to what's going on in the conversation and say, OK, how is

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:13.480
this landing?

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:14.480
And turn it up over time.

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:17.279
That's a better way than the crap sandwich.

00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:18.279
OK.

00:08:18.279 --> 00:08:20.320
A bunch of different questions here.

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:25.160
These are all really good topics, categories, checking in, what are our priorities.

